snippet.textDisplay: I can see both sides of the argument here and it's a tricky one.  I have worked on both sides of the fence and every situation is different. I agree as the owner of a machine you have the right to repair and maintain your equipment. It's yours. But having been in the position where I worked for a manufacturer, a customer got hold of some software and changed some operational parameters in the machine that they didnt fully understand. Then the customer said it was my fault for setting it up wrong and expecting the company to pay, we paid out. Then later found out what was going on. So I can understand manufacturers being slightly hesitant in giving out information on new machines. But I agree as time passes technology moves on this information should become available.
